82","1260":"1260","Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pembridge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Pembridge (Herefs), which is recorded as  <i>Penebrug(g)e</i> from the 11th to 14th centuries. The place-name derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pena</i> + Old English  <i>brycg</i> ‘bridge’. In some cases the surname may be from Pen Bridge in Shipley (Sussex), which derives from an uncertain first element + Old English  <i>brycg</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pember","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of <b>Pamber</b>, a habitational name from a place in Hampshire named Pamber, from Old English <i>penn</i> ‘fold, enclosure’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Pembridge was born about 1257, in Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales, his father, Richard Pembridge, was 37 and his mother, Mrs. Richard Pembridge, was 32. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Richard Pembridge. He died in Wales."},"et":{"about 1257–":"umbes 1257–Surnud","1257–Male":"1257–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1282–1346":"1282–1346","1222–Male":"1222–Surnud","1227–Female":"1227–Surnud","about 1282":"umbes 1282","1227":"1227","1346":"1346","1257":"1257","1222":"1222","about 1257":"umbes 1257","about 1247":"umbes 1247","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 1257–":"noin 1257–Kuollut","1257–Male":"1257–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1282–1346":"1282–1346","1222–Male":"1222–Kuollut","1227–Female":"1227–Kuollut","about 1282":"noin 1282","1227":"1227","1346":"1346","1257":"1257","1222":"1222","about 1257":"noin 1257","about 1247":"noin 1247","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"about 1257–":"environ 1257–Décédé","1257–Male":"1257–Décédé","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","1282–1346":"1282–1346","1222–Male":"1222–Décédé","1227–Female":"1227–Décédée","about 1282":"environ 1282","1227":"1227","1346":"1346","1257":"1257","1222":"1222","about 1257":"environ 1257","about 1247":"environ 1247","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","Pandy, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Pandy, Monmouthshire, Galles","Wales":"Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Pembridge est né environ 1257, à Pandy, Monmouthshire, Galles, son pè